The camera electronics consist of 3 electronics PWBs (printed wiring boards) connected via rigid flex polyimide film layers built into the inner layers of the boards. This integrated approach simplifies the design and manufacturing, and follows the approach used on MER and MSL. The three PWBs are folded into the camera body mechanical housing. The electronics are connected to the rover interface using a 37-pin microD connector. Figure 12 shows the functional block diagram for the ECAM electronics. The pixel transfer rate between the camera and the RCE was increased to 500,000 pixels/second without changing the heritage LVDS clock rate by inserting less space between pixel waveforms. The MER/MSL pixel transfer rate is ∼200,000\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\sim200{,}000$\end{document} pixels per/second. Fig. 12
Perseverance camera electronics block diagram

