The ECAM hardware modes described in Sect. 3.1.6 allow operators to request images of differing pixel scales from the same 20 Megapixel source image. This new capability allows higher-scale image tiles to be inset into lower-scale tiles, offering a combination of wider coverage at lower scale for context and higher scale tiles targeted on particular areas of interest. This context/targeted strategy can be used to significantly reduce overall data volume. Figure 42 shows how this capability might be used for a drive direction planning panorama. The Fig. 42 example includes two quarter-scale frames (1 and 8), 4 half-scale frames (2, 4, 6, and 7), and 2 full-scale frames (3 and 5). Because images 2 through 7 all come from the same original source image, no repointing is required, although re-exposure could occur on frames 2 through 7 if optimal exposure was desired on all frames. The example in Fig. 43 shows how the multi-scale capability might be used for a 360∘\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$360^{\circ}$\end{document} survey panorama. In that example the farther field terrain covered by the full-scale tiles will have a spatial scale more comparable to the near-field spatial scale covered by the lower-scale tiles. Fig. 42
